{"id":"cond-mat/0505239","submitter":"Thomas Schmidt","authors":"T. L. Schmidt, A. Komnik","title":"On the visibility of electron-electron interaction effects in field\n  emission spectra","comments":"7 pages, 3 figures, to appear in Solid State Communications","journal-ref":"Solid State Communications 135 (2005) 455-460","doi":"10.1016/j.ssc.2005.05.014","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":null,"abstract":"  One of the most convenient methods to obtain information about the energy\ndistribution function of electrons in conducting materials is the measurement\nof the energy resolved current $j(\\omega)$ in field emission (FE) experiments.\nIts high energy tail $j_>(\\omega)$ (above the Fermi edge) contains invaluable\ninformation about the nature of the electron--electron interactions inside the\nemitter. Thus far, $j_>(\\omega)$ has been calculated to second order in the\ntunnelling probability, and it turns out to be divergent toward the Fermi edge\nfor a wide variety of emitters. The extraction of the correlation properties\nfrom real experiments can potentially be obscured by the eventually more\ndivergent contributions of higher orders as well as by thermal smearing around\n$E_F$. We present an analysis of both factors and make predictions for the\nenergy window where only the second order tunnelling events dominate the\nbehaviour of $j_>(\\omega)$. We apply our results to the FE from Luttinger\nliquids and single-wall carbon nanotubes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 10 May 2005 11:56:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
